<subSubSection id="10929BEC8DF65335CDE8733E92BCA5EF" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="973385D00D959E9B73FE9E496BCE4911" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BB5DAFA2F3AD9779A55B8EF8C3D62CA1" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName id="DBCB27E3B7F1D1D698B0AF3F120FB6CE" authorityName="Quel.; Mem. Soc. Emul. Montbeliard, Ser. 2, 5: 128" authorityYear="1872" baseAuthorityName="Pers." class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma mesophaeum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis id="AB3686434B2592FE02B95497C999AE34" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed, but apparently uncommon in Greenland with only 11 records (2.9%). This is in contrast to the frequency in Europe, where it is very common and widely distributed (
<bibRefCitation id="8BACE12060AFAED3082AC1A23EF9CCA5" author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
). From alpine and arctic Europe, it is known from the Alps, Southern Carpathians, Svalbard and Iceland. Outside Europe and Greenland, there are a few records from the Rocky Mountains (Colorado, 
<bibRefCitation id="D597F9BBC41E241B0ADA1380DB992E63" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" author="Cripps, C" journalOrPublisher="MycoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 54" refId="B9" refString="Cripps, C, Eberhardt, U, Schuetz, N, Beker, HJ, Evenson, VS, Horak, E, 2019. The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone. MycoKeys 46: 1 - 54, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" title="The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" volume="46" year="2019">Cripps et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
) and arctic Canada (
<bibRefCitation id="CC9F89D8609C4592BCAE9E8DBB05D391" author="Ohenoja, E" journalOrPublisher="North American Fungi" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="85 - 96" refId="B38" refString="Ohenoja, E, Ohenoja, M, 2010. Larger fungi of the Canadian Arctic. North American Fungi 5: 85 - 96" title="Larger fungi of the Canadian Arctic." volume="5" year="2010">Ohenoja and Ohenoja 2010</bibRefCitation>
). It is distributed from the Mediterranean area through the Temperate and Boreal zone to the Arctic and Alpine zones, being less common in the colder areas. Circumpolar, arctic-alpine, temperate, boreal and subarctic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="54BDD8C123857B1703964625B917F0BE" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="A3F13015C760A2547F0BC5A9B3FB7DD7" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="801C0665C807EB932B6D939B7FD71701" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Eleven collections, six of them with 
<taxonomicName id="4B4D2C5B86A36A439D0C9C57A6E6A281" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix glauca" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis id="DA74A1F7C4DFDB1B58180E97C9CD70A6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, one with 
<taxonomicName id="FD810C83A330C4AB198B6D13AED85435" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Dryas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Dryas octopetala" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="octopetala">
<emphasis id="F1ABDC274E6C28A3E78E2B41DB22DB09" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Dryas octopetala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="323C466ADA2B255BE222A24C90525D37" genus="D." lsidName="D. integrifolia" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="integrifolia">
<emphasis id="7577592D3D4EDE086DDBC5D9BB511258" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">D. integrifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, one with 
<taxonomicName id="5CA93BEE8A2C4B1FDDC8C2345A60295A" class="Eudicots" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Bistorta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Bistorta" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CCBB0288B39CD919A2133F998E77BA28" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Bistorta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, three not reported. One record from the Rocky Mountains was also with 
<taxonomicName id="0BCC1E0FEA0DB3B533767CDE7C3420D7" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. glauca" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis id="2E75DCFBFC7D92DFEC4C2998C45AEBEB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The soil conditions were variable. 
<taxonomicName id="A731B6891589AF02A653FD621C5E7352" authorityName="Quel.; Mem. Soc. Emul. Montbeliard, Ser. 2, 5: 128" authorityYear="1872" baseAuthorityName="Pers." class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma mesophaeum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis id="E1F919AA416F14BF591AAFB94E7221C0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread and very versatile when it comes to hosts, including many deciduous as well as coniferous hosts (
<bibRefCitation id="5B4B56CE9DD940F7DFCB750F5B0A426C" author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AF6B59457DB97B8A49E8997524B09DDD" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="notes">
<paragraph id="B535EBAECA77F7B87150D4C58303B390" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="329015BCE1865B156C2F82023E99A57A" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
In 
<bibRefCitation id="34B26E9EDE70F4E4F668563B9110CF3E" author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, it was reported that in arctic and alpine areas there is a chance of confusion with 
<taxonomicName id="A908FA6D7E2B1B26E0DFEC11C1D77016" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. marginatulum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="marginatulum">
<emphasis id="15AEA8B8449B5E6FC745643BD78059E2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. marginatulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, due to the fact that sometimes 
<taxonomicName id="25E884E76B8A564E50BA5474303E8827" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. mesophaeum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis id="79AB44145F133390C93032E1B36CE8B9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, growing in such habitats, tends to have larger spores. They reported that all the 
<normalizedToken id="747C2364E11EA8F6D6A6A275F7256E76" originalValue="‘large-spored’">'large-spored'</normalizedToken>
collections were from Iceland and Svalbard. In Greenland, we have also found collections with larger spores; indeed, nine of the eleven collections discussed here exhibited larger spores in a range from 10.3-11.7 
<normalizedToken id="D02024872191DBF837BCB98CA8873BF1" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6.4-7.1 
<normalizedToken id="55657C4DEC68C858E90E1D8E8E7EEE92" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, a similar range to that reported for Svalbard and Iceland. At the time, 
<bibRefCitation id="004F83E53E7FCCB53D0548DAE411FB6E" author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
did consider creating a variety to address these collections but decided such a course of action was premature and that further study of this variation was required. With regard to the confusion with 
<taxonomicName id="49C90519D1C0B40B16133D1C236DCE1E" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. marginatulum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="marginatulum">
<emphasis id="A3DE15DB8AFDFB25DF2496A46CFD782F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. marginatulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the strongly bicolored cap of 
<taxonomicName id="8353D4A88D42F349C7B1A7A1D680B119" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. mesophaeum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis id="C4459FA9A942A246A83823E82B1E7C51" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should normally aid identification.
</paragraph>
